<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-944  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 944.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 29 1990 v24 n5 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Jury found path through maze of computer law. (Robert T. Morriscomputer virus trial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The jurors in the trial of Robert T. Morris for violating the 1968Computer Fraud and Abuse Act were able to reach a decision inunder six hours in spite of the confusing text of the law.andP;  Inresponse to a request from the jury for a copy of the law, Federaljudge Howard Munson told them they need to consider four points:did Morris intentionally access federal-interest computers withoutauthorization, did he access computers that were in at least twostates, did he cause losses exceeding $1,000 by accessing thecomputers and did he prevent authorized users from using theircomputers? Morris would have been acquitted if there werereasonable doubts as to any of those four elements.andP;  The onlyissue in dispute among the jurors was the question as to whetherMorris intended to cause the damages that resulted from his wormprogram.andP;  Morris was found guilty.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimesComputer virusesLegal Issues.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>